1. DNS “No Response from Server”

Problem:
Client machine could not resolve domain. nslookup returned “No response from server.”

Root Cause:
DNS service was not responding properly and/or firewall profile was misconfigured.

Resolution:

Verified DNS service was running

Checked netstat -an | find ":53" to confirm DNS listening on UDP/TCP

Ensured firewall profiles (Domain/Private/Public) were correctly configured

Verified client DNS settings pointed to 192.168.10.10

Rebuilt DC when necessary to ensure clean DNS configuration

Lesson Learned:
Active Directory is heavily dependent on properly functioning DNS. If DNS fails, the domain effectively fails.

2. DHCP Not Leasing Addresses

Problem:
Client was not receiving IP lease.

Root Cause:
Scope configuration and/or authorization in AD was incomplete.

Resolution:

Created and activated DHCP scope

Authorized DHCP server in Active Directory

Verified lease with ipconfig /all

Confirmed client was set to obtain IP automatically

Lesson Learned:
DHCP must be authorized in AD to function properly in domain environments.

3. GPO Not Applying

Problem:
Group Policy changes (e.g., Control Panel restrictions) did not apply after gpupdate /force.

Root Cause:
OU structure or security filtering misconfiguration.

Resolution:

Verified correct OU placement of user/computer

Confirmed GPO link at proper OU level

Checked security filtering

Logged out/in to refresh user policies

Lesson Learned:
GPO scope is determined by OU hierarchy and security filtering — not just creation.

4. RSAT Not Available

Problem:
Client could not open gpmc.msc.

Root Cause:
RSAT tools not installed on client.

Resolution:

Temporarily configured NAT adapter

Used external router IP to gain internet access

Installed RSAT via Windows Features

Lesson Learned:
Administrative tools must be installed separately on client systems.

5. DNS Listening Only on UDP

Problem:
netstat showed only UDP on port 53.

Investigation:
Confirmed DNS service status and listening behavior.

Lesson Learned:
Understanding service ports and how Windows services bind to interfaces is critical in diagnosing network failures.

